.Dd September 1, 2025
.Dt MDO 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm mdo
.Nd execute commands under different credentials via mac_do(4)
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl u Ar user
.Op Fl i
.Op Fl k
.Op Fl g Ar group
.Op Fl G Ar g1,g2,...
.Op Fl s Ar mods
.Op Fl r | Fl -print-rule
.Op Fl h
.Op Fl -ruid Ar uid
.Op Fl -svuid Ar uid
.Op Fl -euid Ar uid
.Op Fl -rgid Ar gid
.Op Fl -svgid Ar gid
.Op Fl -egid Ar gid
.Op --
.Op Ar command Op args...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility executes the specified
.Ar command
under credentials changed according to rules enforced by
.Xr mac_do 4 .
It provides a userland interface to request credential transitions
without requiring setuid-root binaries.
.Pp
If no
.Ar command
is specified,
.Nm
executes an interactive shell determined by the
.Ev SHELL
environment variable, defaulting to
.Pa /bin/sh .
.Pp
The options are:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl u Ar user
Target user (name or numeric UID).  
If unspecified, defaults to
.Dq root .
.It Fl i
Only change the UID; skip all group changes.  
Equivalent to keeping the caller’s groups while switching user IDs.
.It Fl k
Keep the current user, only change groups.  
This option cannot be combined with
.Fl u
or explicit UID overrides.
.It Fl g Ar group
Override the primary group (name or numeric GID).  
If not provided, the default primary group is taken from the password database
entry of the target user.
.It Fl G Ar g1,g2,...
Set the full list of supplementary groups, replacing defaults.  
Groups can be specified by name or GID, separated by commas.
.It Fl s Ar mods
Modify supplementary groups incrementally.  
The argument is a comma-separated list of tokens:
.Bl -tag -width indent -compact
.It Li @
Reset supplementary groups to empty before applying other modifications.
.It Li + Ns Ar group
Add a group.
.It Li - Ns Ar group
Remove a group.
.El
.It Fl r , Fl -print-rule
Print the equivalent
.Va mac.do.rules
transition clause corresponding to the requested credentials,
instead of executing a command.  
Useful for administrators to generate policy rules.
.It Fl h
Display usage information.
.El
.Ss Advanced UID/GID Overrides
The following long options allow setting individual credential components
explicitly:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl -ruid Ar uid
Set real UID.
.It Fl -svuid Ar uid
Set saved UID.
.It Fl -euid Ar uid
Set effective UID.
.It Fl -rgid Ar gid
Set real GID.
.It Fl -svgid Ar gid
Set saved GID.
.It Fl -egid Ar gid
Set effective GID.
.El
These may be combined with group modifications for fine-grained transitions.
.Pp
Credentials are applied atomically using
.Xr setcred 2 .
All requests are subject to authorization by
.Xr mac_do 4 .
.Sh EXAMPLES
Run a command as another user:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
mdo -u alice id
.Ed
.Pp
Run with explicit primary and supplementary groups:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
mdo -u 1001 -g wheel -G staff,operator /bin/sh
.Ed
.Pp
Modify only supplementary groups for the current user:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
mdo -k -s @,+wheel,+operator /usr/bin/id
.Ed
.Pp
Request an advanced transition with explicit IDs:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
mdo --ruid 1002 --svgid 1003 --egid 1004 /bin/id
.Ed
.Pp
Print the rule string corresponding to a requested transition:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
mdo -u bob -g wheel -G staff -r
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr mac_do 4 ,
.Xr setcred 2 ,
.Xr su 1 ,
.Xr doas 1
.Sh HISTORY
The
.Nm
command first appeared in
.Fx 14.2 .
Support for explicit UID/GID overrides, supplementary group control,
group-only transitions, and rule printing was added in
.Fx 15.0
as part of Google Summer of Code 2025.
